{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537132"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15908"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15908"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.17,0.03,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63098"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8599"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48549"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"5479"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about her risk of developing ovarian cancer. Her mother died from ovarian cancer at age 45. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou decide to review the current evidence about risk factors for ovarian cancer. You find a study that identified 250 women with ovarian cancer from hospital records and compared their talcum powder use to 250 age-matched women without ovarian cancer from the same geographic area.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Case-control study","Cross-sectional study","Ecological study","Randomised controlled trial","Cohort study"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis research describes a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecase-control study\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an observational study that starts with a group of people who have a condition (cases) and compares them to a group without the condition (controls) to identify potential risk factors or exposures. In this example, women with ovarian cancer are the cases, and women without ovarian cancer are the controls, with talcum powder use being the exposure of interest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecross-sectional study\u003C/strong\u003E examines the relationship between diseases and other variables of interest as they exist in a defined population at a single point in time. It would not be appropriate for studying rare conditions like ovarian cancer as it would require an extremely large sample size to identify enough cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecohort study\u003C/strong\u003E follows groups of people forward in time to see who develops the outcome of interest. While this can provide stronger evidence than case-control studies, it would be impractical for studying ovarian cancer due to its relative rarity and the long follow-up time required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erandomised controlled trial\u003C/strong\u003E would not be ethical or practical in this context as you cannot randomly assign people to use talcum powder to study cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eecological study\u003C/strong\u003E looks at groups of people rather than individuals, often comparing disease rates between different populations or time periods. It would not allow for detailed analysis of individual risk factors like talcum powder use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECase-control studies are particularly useful for studying rare conditions or when examining multiple potential risk factors. Their main limitations include recall bias (as exposure information is collected retrospectively) and selection bias in choosing appropriate controls. However, they are often the most practical study design for investigating risk factors for rare conditions like ovarian cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Case-control studies are retrospective studies that compare people with a condition (cases) to those without it (controls) to identify potential risk factors.","Selection of appropriate controls is crucial in case-control studies to minimise bias.","Case-control studies are particularly useful for rare conditions or when studying multiple potential exposures."],"references":["Lu CY. Observational studies: a review of study designs, challenges and strategies to reduce confounding. Int J Clin Pract. 2009;63(5):691-697. doi:10.1111/j.1742-1241.2009.02056.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48549"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48549"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T02:18:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T02:21:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8599"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63098"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type